Creating a Sense of Urgency A while back I had this girlfriend. We had a lot of fun, but she was hesitant to commit to me. No matter what I tried, she just wouldn&rsquo;t become &ldquo;official.&rdquo;
Then, there was this other time—with another girlfriend—and I was the one having a hard time committing to her. We had a great time together, all systems go, but I couldn&rsquo;t help but wonder what else was out there&hellip;
In both relationships, a committment was finally made. But SOMETHING WAS NEEDED TO. Can you guess what it was? I&rsquo;ll tell you.
A breakup.
And both times the dumper came crawling back.
When we feel like we might lose something—especially when we perceive that thing as being good for us—the game changes. Suddenly, it&rsquo;s time to shit or get off the pot. And caught with a case of ameobic dysintery, we discover we have to shit real bad.
That feeling of scarcity is a powerful motivator—one you&rsquo;re wise to exploit in every piece of copy you write. I&rsquo;ll tell you why.
Because even after the perfect pitch, an unbelievable offer, people won&rsquo;t take action. They&rsquo;ll want to think it over. They&rsquo;ll hem and haw. They&rsquo;ll move on. So you have to find a way to spur them into action. Otherwise&hellip;
They need to be tipped over the edge
They&rsquo;ll probably find themselves another boyfriend or girlfriend&hellip;
So you have to stoke that fire with the fear of loss. Give your prospects a reason to buy now. Create that scarcity, the deadline, every time. The possibilities for doing so are limited only by your imagination. Here are a few examples to get you started.
